          <title>Procedure Indications</title>
          <text>Patient is a 34-year-old G2P1 female at 38 weeks and 4 days gestation presenting for scheduled repeat cesarean delivery. Prior cesarean in 2022 for failure to progress. Current pregnancy complicated by gestational hypertension. Fetal presentation cephalic. Patient and obstetrician mutually agreed upon elective repeat cesarean section. Risks and benefits of repeat cesarean versus trial of labor after cesarean (TOLAC) were discussed in detail at prior prenatal visits. Patient declined TOLAC.</text>
        </section>
      </component>
      <!-- Procedure Description (LOINC 10219-4) -->
      <component>
        <section>
          <templateId root="2.16.840.1.113883.10.20.22.2.29"/>
          <code code="10219-4" codeSystem="2.16.840.1.113883.6.1" displayName="Procedure Description"/>
          <title>Procedure Description</title>
          <text>Patient was brought to operating room and placed in supine position with left lateral tilt. Spinal anesthesia was administered without complication. Pfannenstiel incision was made through prior scar. Sharp and blunt dissection was carried down through subcutaneous tissue. The bladder flap was created and the uterine incision made in a low transverse fashion. A live male infant was delivered in vertex presentation with Apgar scores 8 and 9 at 1 and 5 minutes respectively. Birth weight 3,420 grams. The placenta was delivered manually and was complete. Uterus was closed in two layers with 0-Vicryl suture. Fascia closed with 0-Vicryl. Skin closed with subcuticular 4-0 Monocryl. Estimated blood loss 450 mL. No complications. Sponge, instrument, and needle counts correct x3.</text>
        </section>
      </component>
